\f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} how to?;copying;pasting}}{\fs16\up6  }Copying and moving references between open files
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
You might want to transfer references from one file to another, for example if you wanted to maintain separate databases on different topics whose subjects happened to overlap somewhat.  Or you might want to transfer references from an on-line search you 
just imported to an exiting {\i Refs} file.  This is easily accomplished with either the mouse or keyboard, as follows:
\par 
\par Keyboard:  Select the references you wish to copy or move, in a file window.  Then use {\b Cut/Copy/Paste} from the edit menu to copy or move the references to another file window.  This procedure does {\b not}
 use the clipboard, so you can't paste references into other applications this way, I'm afraid.
\par 
\par Mouse:{\f24\fs28 \tab }Select the references you wish to copy or move.  Then click on your selection with the {\b right}
 mouse button.  The cursor changes to a reference card, or a stack of them.  Now drag to the target window and release the mouse button. 
\par \pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar 
\par \pard \widctlpar By default, references are copied, not moved.  If you wish to move the references and remove them from the original file, hold down the {\b shift}
 key while dragging (specifically, the shift key must be down when you release the right mouse button).
\par 
\par You can set {\i Refs} to ask you for confirmation of mouse drag operations under the {\b Options, Confirmation...} command.
\par 
\par Drag and drop also works to the bibliography window, if it exists.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb120\sa120\widctlpar \cbpat16 \b\i\f4\fs48\cf2\lang2057 \page {\cs15\f5\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} Biblio}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 $
} Using bibliographies}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} bibliography;how to?}}{\fs16\up6  }Creating and using a bibliography
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 The contents of the bibliography are maintained by the program regardless of closing, opening and creating new files, so you can easily compile a bibliography from several source databases.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Adding references from database windows
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 1. \tab}\pard \fi-283\li283\nowidctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnb0\pni0\pnf5\pnfs20\pnstart1\pnindent283\pnhang{\pntxta . }}Select the references you wish to add to the bibliography.
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 2. \tab}Choose {\b Reference, Add to bibliography}, or use the toolbar button ({\b\fs28\cf2 +}).  If the Bibliography was previously empty, a bibliography window will be created automatically.
\par \pard \nowidctlpar 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Adding references to the bibliography while editing the reference
\par \pard\plain \nowidctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par The menu item {\b File, add to bibliography} is a toggle; if the item is checked, the reference is in the bibliography, and choosing the command will remove the reference from the bibliography rather than adding it.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par References currently in the bibliography are shown a different colour from the others.  In the bibliography window, different colouring is also used.  Coloured references are also to be found in a currently open file, whereas normal colouring indicates th
at the file this reference is from has been closed, or the reference has been deleted from that file.  Either way, the bibliography has the sole remaining copy of the reference in memory, and deleting it will be permanent.
\par 
\par To remove references from the bibliography, select the bibliography window.  You may now use {\b Reference, Delete}
 as usual to remove the references.  However, in this case the references are not removed from memory unless they are not from any of the currently open files.  If the deletion results in the bibliography becoming empty, the bibliography
 window is automatically destroyed.
\par 
\par To empty the bibliography, simply close the bibliography window.
\par 
\par The bibliography window can display its contents in two ways; either as a reference database very similar to normal database windows, or as formatted text for editing and copying to the clipboard.  You can toggle between these displays with the {\b 
Options, Display formatted bibliography} command.  This window displays your file in the currently selected printer font, so you can use this as a crude form of print preview.
\par 
\par Depending on the state of this toggle, you can save the bibliography contents as either a database or as a standard text file, using {\b File, Save As}.
\par 
\par New bibliography formats can be created and entered using {\b Options, bibliography format}.  See {\strike bibliography format syntax}{\v BibSyntax} for details.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb120\sa120\widctlpar \cbpat16 \b\i\f4\fs48\cf2\lang2057 \page {\cs15\f5\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} AddImport}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {
\cs15\fs16\up6 $} Adding/removing import DLLs}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} importing files;customizing}}{\b0\i0\f2\fs16\cf0\up6  }Adding/removing import/export filters
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
The Import/Export feature is designed to be easily expandable with new formats.  Covered so far are MedLine, BioSys, Current Contents, Chemical Abstracts, Refer and BIDS, although of these Refer is at present the only one with export capability.  This hel
p file also contains information for programmers wishing to write their own import filters.  See {\strike Import filter Interface}{\v DLLinterface}  for details.
\par 
\par Please note that Current Contents and Chemical Abstracts are currently only available as 16-bit filters, and will not work with the 32-bit version.
\par 
\par Letting Refs know about new filters is easily accomplished.  You don't need to do anything!  The filter should have the filetype of {\b FLT}.  Just copy it into your {\i Refs} directory, and {\i Refs} will find it automatically.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb120\sa120\widctlpar \cbpat16 \b\i\f4\fs48\cf2\lang2057 \page {\cs15\f5\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} Import}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 $
} Importing other format databases}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} importing files;opening files;how to?}}Importing/exporting other database formats
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\i Refs} can theoretically read references from any reference file format.  Each format needs to have an import filter written for it (such as BIDS.FLT), to deal with the foreign format.  {\i Refs}
 can deal with up to 32 foreign formats.  At present, I have written such filters only for ISI (BIDS) and Medline.  Several forms of Medline are supported, including Biosys, WinSpirs and the on-line service.
\par 
\par Filters for the {\strike Chemical Abstracts}{\v ChemAb} and Current Contents Reference Manager are also included in the 16-bit version of {\i Refs}, and they were written by Mats Valli.  I do not know when he will produce 32-bit versions.
\par 
\par \pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar 1.\tab Select {\b File, Import... }and a dialog will appear listing the available formats known to {\i Refs}.  This will look something like the following diagram.  Select a format, and choose {\b OK}.
\par 
\par \pard \qc\fi-360\li360\widctlpar \{bmcwd impexp.bmp\}
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar 2.\tab Some filters may have an options function.  If so, the {\b Options}
 button will be available to allow you to call this function.  This typically displays version information and allows you to modify the filter's behaviour.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar 3.\tab Choose {\b OK.  }Double-clicking the desired format will also close the dialog box, as if you'd selected it and then clicked {\b OK}.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar 4.\tab Select the file to import in the next dialog box.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-360\li360\widctlpar 5.\tab {\i Refs}
 will then import the file as well as the filter can manage.  Imports may well lose some information, depending on the capabilities of the format being imported.  The imported file will appear as a new database window.
\par 
\par \pard \widctlpar Programmers wishing to write their own import filters are referred to the {\strike Import filter Interface}{\v DLLinterface} section.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb120\sa120\widctlpar \cbpat16 \b\i\f4\fs48\cf2\lang2057 \page {\cs15\f5\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} FindRef}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 
$} Finding a reference}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} how to?;searching;finding}}{\fs16\up6  }How to find a reference
\par \pard\plain \fi-504\li504\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 1.\tab 
Check whether the windows you want to search are searchable, and adjust as necessary.  This is done with the check-box in the bottom left of each database window.  If the box is checked the window will be searched.
\par 
\par 2.\tab Select {\b New search...} from the {\b Search }menu, press {\b F3}, or choose the search toolbar button.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-504\li504\widctlpar 3.\tab From the {\b Search By} combo box choose the type of search you wish to perform.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-504\li504\widctlpar 4.\tab In the {\b Search For} box type the string you wish to search for.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par \pard \fi-504\li504\widctlpar 5.\tab Use the three check-boxes to tell {\i Refs} whether to search case sensitively, whether to search for all references {\i except} those satisfying your conditions, and thirdly whether to {\strike 
search using regular expressions}{\v regexp} for added flexibility.  If this third box is checked, {\i Refs}
 will treat the string you are searching for as a regular expression to use, otherwise it will simply look for the text you give.  Regular expression matching is much more sophisticated, but slower.
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f5\fs20 6. \tab}\pard \fi-283\li283\widctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlbody\pndec\pnb0\pni0\pnf5\pnfs20\pnstart6\pnindent283\pnhang{\pntxta . }}Choose {\b OK}
.  A new window will then show all references matching your criteria.  This window will automatically be marked non-searchable, unless it is saved as a file later.  The title bar initially contains a description of how the references were found, until it 
is saved as a file, when it becomes a normal file window.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par Note that the new window does not contain copies of the data in the original files; it contains pointers to the original data.  This means that if you edit a reference in a search wi
ndow, it will also be updated in the file from which it originally came (as long as that file is still open).
\par \pard \fi-540\li540\widctlpar 
\par 7.\tab You're not content with the results?  Too many references?  You can restrict the search, by now selecting {\b  Search, Narrow search...}
  This will repeat steps 2-4, but this time will perform the search only on those references you found last time (i.e., those which are currently displayed).
\par 
