\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Description of search criteria
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par When a search is made, the new window has the criteria used to find the references in its title bar.
\par Each criterion is contained in braces {\b \{ \}} and combined by the symbols {\b +} and {\b ,}.
\par 
\par \tab {\b +}\tab References in both sets (logical AND)
\par \tab {\b ,}\tab References in either set (logical OR)
\par 
\par In addition, the expression inside the braces may contain a {\b !} which indicates that the search was for references that did {\i not} match the criteria.  For example:
\par 
\par \{\{ Author = "Fred" \} + \{ Date = !"1991"\}\} , \{ Author = "Joe" \}
\par 
\par This search now contains all references written by Fred (but not in 1991), plus all those by Joe.  This was generated by searching for Author Fred, then Narrow Search, select logical NOT and Date 1991, and finally Expand Search for Author Joe.
\par \pard\plain \s1\sb120\sa120\widctlpar \cbpat16 \b\i\f4\fs48\cf2\lang2057 \page {\cs15\f5\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 #} regexp}${\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 $
} Regular expressions}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} how to?;searching;finding}}{\fs16\up6  }Searching using regular expressions
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\i Refs} can perform more sophisticated pattern matching using UNIX-style {\i regular expressions}
.  It uses the UNIX type of regular expression since this is considerably more powerful than regular expression routines commonly found in Windows programs.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Regular expression syntax
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par Regular expressions take a little effort to learn, but once mastered they allow you to search for some really quite complex conditions.  The following information is taken from the original UNIX manual page for this regular expression library.
\par 
\par 1.\tab A regular expression is zero or more {\i branches} separated by \lquote |\rquote 
.  It matches anything that matches one of the branches (so you can use this for looking for one expression OR another, as an alternative to searching once and then using Expand Search).
\par 
\par 2.\tab A branch is zero or more {\i pieces}, concatenated.  It matches these pieces in order.
\par 
\par 3.\tab A piece is an {\i atom} possibly followed by \lquote *\rquote , \lquote +\rquote  or \lquote ?\rquote .  An atom followed by \lquote *\rquote  matches 0 or more matches of the atom.  \lquote +\rquote  matches 1 or more matches of the atom, \lquote 
?\rquote  matches 1 match of the atom or no match.
\par \pard \nowidctlpar 
\par 4.\tab An atom can be a character, which will be matched exactly, or a number of special constructs as laid out below:
\par 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx1440\cellx9468 \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b .\cell }Matches any single character\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx1440\cellx9468 \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b (}{\b\i regexp}{\b )\cell }
Matches the complete regular expression within the parentheses\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b ^\cell }The beginning of the field being searched\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b $\cell }
The end of the field being searched\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b [}{\b\i range}{\b ]\cell }Matches any of a range of characters  (see below)\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b \\n\cell }
Matches a newline\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b \\\\\cell }Matches a single \\\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b \\(\cell }Matches a single (\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \trowd 
\trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx1440\cellx9468 \pard \nowidctlpar\intbl {\b \\)\cell }Matches a single )\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \nowidctlpar 
\par Note that characters that might otherwise be interpreted as special (any of + . * ( ) $ ^ [ ] or \\ ) must be preceded by a \\ if you want to match the character itself, and not its regexp meaning.  For example, (96) matches anything with \lquote 96
\rquote  in it.  To match only things containing \lquote (96)\rquote  you need \lquote \\(96\\)\rquote .
\par 
\par 5.\tab A range can be any group of characters ( e.g. \lquote [aeiou]\rquote  for all the vowels ) or certain groups of characters, for instance \lquote [0-9]\rquote  will match any digit.  To match a \lquote -\lquote 
 in a range, make it the first or last character in the range, eg [a-z-] matches all lowercase letters and \lquote -\lquote .  To match anything {\b except} what\rquote s in the range, use a ^, e.g. [^aeiou] will match any character that is not a vowel.

\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Examples
\par \pard\plain \nowidctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par This is quite complex, so here are some examples:
\par 
\par To search for anything mentioning the word \lquote colour\rquote  in either British or American spelling, use {\b colou?r} or {\b col(o|ou)r} both of which will achieve the desired result.
\par 
\par To search for all references mentioning either cdc25 or wee1, you might use {\b (cdc25|wee1)}
\par 
\par To match any author whose name begins with F and ends with m, you might use {\b F[^, ]m}
\par 
\par Or to match DNA sequences of at least three base pairs you could use: {\b [ACGT][ACGT][ACGT]+}
\par You could even look for more complex sequences:  {\b TATA[AGCT]*A[GC]T} matches TATA followed by any number of nucleotides followed by A followed by G or C followed by T.
\par 
