\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 These formats are stored in REFS.INI (in {\i Refs} for Windows\'ae 3.1), or in the HKEY_CURRENT_USER part of the Registry in the Windows NT\'99 and Windows\'ae 95 version.
\par 
\par To create a new format, or change an existing one, choose {\b Options, Bibliography format}.  The following dialog will appear:
\par 
\par \pard \qc\widctlpar \{bmcwd bibfmt.bmp\}
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par To create a new format choose {\b New} or to edit one select the format to edit and choose {\b Edit}.  Each format must have a unique name, and when creating a new one {\i Refs} will complain if you use a name that already exists.
\par 
\par A format line looks something like:
\par {\f3 
\par [prefix][suffix]<A}{\i\f3 N}{\f3 @, ><T@>\\n< J@, ><V@><N/@ ><P@ ><D(@)>
\par }
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Prefix and suffix sections:
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par There may be one (prefix only) or two (prefix and su
ffix) of these sections.  The characters inside these sections are attached at the beginning or end of the completed set of formatted references.  This is primarily for use in creating bibliographies in document processing languages, such as RTF or TeX.  
If these are present, the [ character must be either (a) the first character in the format, or (b) immediately follow the ] of the prefix section.  Otherwise, Refs will begin interpreting as the main reference format string.  So:
\par 
\par {\f3 [foo\\n][bar] Hello.\\n
\par }
\par Will format as:
\par 
\par {\f4 foo
\par Hello.
\par .
\par .
\par .
\par bar
\par }
\par Whereas
\par 
\par {\f3 [foo\\n] [bar] Hello.\\n
\par }
\par will format as:
\par 
\par {\f4 foo
\par [bar] Hello.
\par .
\par .
\par .
\par }
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 How fields work:
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par The uppercase letters ABCDEIJKNPRTVX are the {\b field tags } and have the same meanings as they do in the Refer file format.  See {\strike Technical notes}{\v Tech}
 for an explanation of the tag meanings.  They are mostly fairly self evident.  Once the field has been determined, the remaining characters are literally copied (with some exceptions, see {\b Special characters }below), so if your reference
 has Date field of '1992', {\f3 <D(@)>} will produce '(1992)' when formatted, and nothing if the date field is empty.
\par 
\par Fields begin with a <.  The next character must be a valid field tag character, or an exclamation mark.  If it is an exclamation mark, the next character must be the field tag, and then this field will only be formatted if the field is {\i not}
 filled.  If this field does or does not exist, as appropriate, in the reference, the other characters in the field will be printed until a > is encountered, ot
herwise parsing continues to the matching > character, so the field and any nested fields are missed out (see {\b Nesting fields }
below).  The symbol @ indicates where in the field to insert the field text itself, unless the field tag was preceded by an exclamation mark, in which case the @ character itself is added.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Sub-formatting of Author and Editor fields:
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par The tag characters 'A' and 'E' may be followed by a detailed format specification.  The general structure is:
\par 
\par <A[{\i type}[{\i options}]\'85>
\par 
\par Where {\i type} is the number 1, 2 or 3, which correspond to the three Author formatting options available in the {\strike Main List Options}{\v ListOpt} dialog as follows:
\par 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx1080\cellx5130 \pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b Type\cell Description\cell }\pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b \row }\trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx1080\cellx5130 \pard \widctlpar\intbl 1\cell All authors\cell \pard 
