\cs15\fs16\up6 $} Options for sorting names}K{\footnote \pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 K} customizing;sorting}} Sorting by name
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 This dialog box gives some options that you can change to affect how {\i Refs} interprets and sorts by the names given for authors and editors.
\par 
\par \pard \qc\widctlpar \{bmcwd namesort.bmp\}
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par As with the other sorting options, these options are stored on a per-window basis, and the most recently chosen options are used for defaults in new files and saved to your {\i Refs}
 configuration when you exit the program. The two radio buttons are the two main comparison methods:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 First given name{\b0 
\par }\pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 This is how {\i Refs}
 used to sort all the time.  It is a plain comparison of the two author entries.  If you enter all your authors as, say 'Smith, J', then this will work perfectly for you.  It is very much faster than the next method.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Family name
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\i Refs} uses the remaining options to try to work out which word in the name is the fam
ily name, compare that first, and then compare the first name and/or initials.  First it checks whether you have explicitly put the family name first.  You do this by putting a separator in the name.  By default this separator is a comma, but it can be an
y single character other than a space or tab.  If {\i Refs}
 finds the separator, it assumes that everything before the separator is the family name, and everything after it is the first name and initials.  If Refs does not find the separator, it looks at the next option to see what to do next.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Examples
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 If you set 'surname usually last' and have a ',' separator {\i Refs} will interpret names as follows:
\par "Cutts, Tim" \tab Family name: "Cutts" \tab First name and initials "Tim"
\par "Tim Cutts" \tab Family name: "Cutts" \tab First name and initials "Tim"
\par "Cutts" \tab Family name: "Cutts" \tab First name and initials: none
\par \pard\plain \s3\li360\widctlpar \b\f5\lang2057 {\b0\fs20 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb120\widctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Family name usually last
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par {\i Refs}
 looks at this setting to establish whether in  your language, you usually write the family name last (the English do, the Chinese don't, for example).  Either way, it assumes that the last or first word in the name, as appropriate, is the family name, an
d sorts on that basis.
\par 
\par {\b\cf6 NB:}
\par {\i Refs} does not do this perfectly.  {\i Refs} will guess wrong for names like 'de Montfort' or others where there is more than one word in the surname.  {\i Refs} will see the family name (for sorting purposes, anyway) as 'Montfort'.  For su
ch names you will have to put the family name first followed by a separator if you want it to be sorted by the first word of the family name.  Family names with hyphens, such as 'Fotherington-Smythe', do not have this problem.
