\pard\plain \s16\widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 +} bib-rtf}}Bibliography formatting using RTF
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par The following tutorial was written by Ian Carpenter:
\par 
\par Whilst {\i Refs} can currently only e
xport data in a pure ANSI text format, it is possible to apply simple formatting commands to the bibliography output by using Rich Text Format (RTF). This is a pure text format defined by Microsoft to allow formatted data transfer between applications. Wo
rd for Windows and most other common Windows\'ae
 word processors can export and import documents in this format without losing much formatting information. Unfortunately the RTF specification (version 1.4) is a 101 page document with 866 different control word
s! Hence, this short and simple guide to formatting using RTF.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 RTF file structure
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par An RTF file consists of two main parts: the header and the document. The header indicates that the file is in RTF format and includes some document information such as character set, font table, file table, colour table and a stylesheet. For the simple fo
rmatting that is generally required for bibliographies not all of these entries are needed.
\par 
\par Control words within an RTF file signify formatting properties. These properties may be applied to the whole file or just to a portion of the document. A {\i group} is a part of the file that is enclosed with curly brackets \{\}
. Any control words within a group only apply to the information in that group. An entire RTF file is considered a group and must be enclosed in braces.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Control word syntax
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\b\fs24 
\par }All control words take the following form:
\par 
\par \pard \qc\widctlpar {\b\fs24 \\LetterSequence}{\b\i\fs24 <}{\b\fs24 Delimiter}{\b\i\fs24 >
\par }\pard \widctlpar 
\par Note that a backslash begins each control word. In the {\i Refs} format specification a backslash can be inserted by adding {\b TWO} backslashes (because \\ on its own has some special meanings in the bibliography format syntax).
\par 
\par The LetterSequence is made up of lowercase alphabetic characters between "a" and "z" inclusive. RTF is case sensitive, and all RTF control words must be in lowercase.
\par 
\par The Delimiter marks the end of an RTF control word, and can be one of the following:
\par \pard \fi-360\li720\widctlpar\tx720 {\f1 \'b7\tab }A space. In this case, the space is part of the control word. The space does not appear in the document.
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }
A digit or a hyphen (-), which indicates that a numeric parameter follows. The subsequent digital sequence is then delimited by a space or any character other than a letter or a digit. The parameter can be a positive or a negative number. The range of the
 values for the number is \_32767 through 32767. 
\par {\f1 \'b7\tab }Any character other than a letter or a digit. In this case, the delimiting character terminates the control word but is not actually part of the control word.
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par Any characters following the delimiter, including spaces, will appear in the document. For this reason, you should use spaces only where necessary; do not use spaces merely to break up RTF code.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Header structure
\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\b\fs24 
\par }This looks complicated, I know.  Don\rquote t worry\'85 there are some examples coming up to help you!  To allow the setting of font name, font size and general font properties the control words required in the header are:
\par 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108\trbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw15 \cellx1440\cellx8460 \pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b Control word\cell Description\cell }\pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b \row }\trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx1440\cellx8460 \pard \sb120\widctlpar\intbl {\b \\
rtf1}\cell Defines the RTF format and gives the version number (1 is the current major version number)\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b \\ansi}\cell Defines the character set. \\ansi is the default. Other possible sets are:
\line \\mac\tab Apple Macintosh\line \\pc\tab IBM PC code page 437\line \\pca \tab IBM PC code page 850, used by IBM Personal System/2{\fs12 \'ae} \cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b \\fonttbl}\cell '\{' {\b \\}{\b\fs8 \~}{\b 
fonttbl }(<fontinfo> | ('\{' <fontinfo> '\}'))+  '\}'\line Defines a font table containing each font to be used in the document, in the following format:\line {\b <fontinfo>}\tab <fontnum><fontfamily><fcharset><fprq><fontname>\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl 
\row \pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b \\f}{\b\i N}{\b \cell }Set the font number to {\i N}. This number is used to refer to the font in the rest of the document.\cell \pard \widctlpar\intbl \row \pard \widctlpar\intbl {\b \\f}{\b\i FAMILY}{\b \cell }
Set the font family. A font family allows applications to attempt to intelligently choose fonts if the exact font is not present on the reading system. RTF uses the following control words to describe the various font families.
\par {\b 
\par nil}\tab \tab Unknown or default font
\par {\b roman}\tab \tab Roman, proportionally spaced serif font
\par {\b swiss}\tab \tab Swiss, proportionally spaced sans serif fonts
\par {\b modern}\tab Fixed-pitch serif and sans serif fonts
\par {\b script}\tab \tab Script fonts
\par {\b decor}\tab \tab Decorative fonts
