\par \pard\plain \widctlpar \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\b\fs24 
\par }When combining RTF control words with the bibliography format syntax used in {\i Refs} it is quite possible to make small and subtle mistakes that can render the RTF difficult or impossible to read for a word processor. Common mistakes include:
\par {\fs24 
\par }\pard \fi-360\li720\widctlpar\tx720\tx5040 {\f1 \'b7}\tab Mismatched brackets. The number of open brackets \ldblquote \{\ldblquote  must be the same as the number of close brackets \ldblquote \}\rdblquote 
 space. It is important to understand how the curly brackets are splitting the reference into groups.
\par {\f1 
\par \'b7}\tab Missing spaces. Control words must be correctly terminated. Often this is achieved by the following control word but for the last one in a group a space is required. So,
\par 
\par \tab {\f11 \{\\\\f0\\\\fs24\\\\b This is some text\}}\tab will produce 12 point bold font 0 text,
\par 
\par \tab {\f11 \{\\\\f0\\\\fs24\\\\bThis is some text\}}\tab will not work correctly.
\par 
\par \tab In this case a space is required after the bold command.
\par 
\par {\f1 \'b7}\tab Missing backslashes. Every control word begins with a backslash but in the {\i Refs} bibliography format editor, {\b TWO} backslashes are required i.e. {\f11 \\\\}.
\par \pard \widctlpar {\fs24 
\par }\pard\plain \s2\sb120\nowidctlpar \b\f5\cf9\lang2057 Summary
